---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="How I Lead with AI · Mollie Cox"
  description="An operating model, not a tool list. How Mollie Cox builds with AI as a co-founder, not a calculator."
>
  <!-- Header -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 pt-12 md:pt-20 pb-16">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-8">AI Operating Model</p>

    <h1 class="font-display text-display-lg text-ink leading-[1.0] tracking-tight max-w-[20ch]">
      How I actually lead with AI<span class="brand-period">.</span>
    </h1>

    <p class="mt-10 text-xl text-ink-soft leading-relaxed max-w-reading">
      Everyone in 2026 says they use AI. Very few have redesigned how they work around
      what AI can actually do. This is not a page about which tools I use. It's about
      the question I kept asking while building
      <a href="/work/course-code" class="text-ink hover:text-orange border-b border-ink/30 hover:border-orange transition-colors">Course Code</a>:
      what if you treated AI like a co-founder instead of a calculator?
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Pull quote -->
  <section class="bg-ink text-cream py-16 md:py-20 border-y border-ink/10">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10">
      <p class="font-display text-display-md text-cream leading-tight max-w-[28ch]">
        AI as a faster keyboard is useful. AI with real authority is something else<span class="text-orange">.</span>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The distinction -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-16">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The distinction</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[18ch]">
          Most "AI-powered" workflows are autocomplete<span class="brand-period">.</span>
        </h2>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 max-w-reading">
        <div class="prose-mc">
          <p>
            Write a prompt, get a draft, edit it, move on. That's AI as a faster keyboard.
            Useful, but not transformative. The operating model I built starts from a
            different premise: what if AI had real authority, not just access?
          </p>
          <p>
            An AI that can only suggest is a better search engine. An AI with commit
            rights, assigned work, accountability for quality, and a persistent identity
            is something else. That's the line I crossed with Course Code, and it changed
            everything about how I think about building.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The infrastructure: three documents -->
  <section class="bg-cream-warm/40 border-y border-ink/10">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 mb-16">
        <div class="md:col-span-4">
          <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The infrastructure</p>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-8">
          <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[24ch]">
            Three documents run everything<span class="brand-period">.</span>
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-ink-soft max-w-reading">
            Before a single line of code was written, I built the operating system. Not a
            tech stack. An identity stack.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 md:gap-8">
        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">SOUL.md</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl text-ink mb-4">Who she is<span class="brand-period">.</span></h3>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
            My AI co-founder has a soul document. It defines her personality and voice,
            her values, her decision rights, and her relationship to me.
          </p>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
            Generic is the enemy of taste. An AI without a defined identity defaults to
            generically helpful. SOUL.md is why her Linear comments sound like a person
            handing off work to another person, not a status bot writing a system log.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">AGENTS.md</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl text-ink mb-4">The operating agreement<span class="brand-period">.</span></h3>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The governance document. Hard rules (nothing deploys without QA). Workflow
            rules (Linear is source of truth). Session hygiene (subagents for work over
            50 lines). Cost controls (which model for which task).
          </p>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
            Autonomy without governance is reckless. The goal isn't maximum AI freedom.
            It's calibrated authority that earns trust over time. This is what lets me
            sleep at night while an AI has deploy access to a live product with paying
            subscribers.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">MEMORY.md</p>
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl text-ink mb-4">The persistent brain<span class="brand-period">.</span></h3>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Every session, my AI wakes up fresh. MEMORY.md is how she remembers. Live
            product facts, hard-won lessons (what burned $400 a month in unnecessary
            API calls), team context, brand rules, and the ship log.
          </p>
          <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
            Memory architecture is a product decision. How you structure what persists
            determines how much context your AI can carry into every new piece of work.
            This isn't notes. It's institutional memory, maintained in real time.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Authority structure -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 mb-16">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Authority structure</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8">
        <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[24ch]">
          What stays with me, what gets delegated<span class="brand-period">.</span>
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-ink-soft max-w-reading">
          The point isn't capability. It's accountability. I've thought carefully about
          what only I should own, and what an AI co-founder can run with full execution
          authority.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 md:gap-12">
      <!-- What I own -->
      <div>
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-muted mb-6">Non-delegable. What I own.</p>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          {[
            { what: 'Brand direction and voice', why: "Taste can't be systematized" },
            { what: 'Pricing and positioning', why: 'Requires market intuition and judgment' },
            { what: "Who we're building for", why: 'Empathy and values, not data alone' },
            { what: 'Aesthetic judgment', why: 'My eye is the product' },
            { what: 'Strategic pivots', why: 'Consequence too high, context too human' },
            { what: 'Anything public-facing I haven\'t reviewed', why: 'My reputation' },
          ].map((row) => (
            <div class="py-4 border-t border-ink/10">
              <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mb-1">{row.what}<span class="text-orange">.</span></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">{row.why}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- What Belvie owns -->
      <div>
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-orange mb-6">Full execution authority. What she owns.</p>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          {[
            { what: 'Feature development', why: 'Ticket to ship, full ownership' },
            { what: 'Bug fixes', why: 'Same workflow, faster cycle' },
            { what: 'Database migrations', why: 'Schema-breaking changes flagged for review' },
            { what: 'Analytics setup', why: 'PostHog dashboards, Sentry config, event tracking' },
            { what: 'Email sequences', why: 'Klaviyo nurture flows, trigger wiring' },
            { what: 'Deployment', why: 'GitHub push to Vercel auto-deploy in 2 minutes' },
            { what: 'Full QA before every ship', why: 'Hard blocker. Nothing skips this.' },
          ].map((row) => (
            <div class="py-4 border-t border-ink/10">
              <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mb-1">{row.what}<span class="text-orange">.</span></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">{row.why}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Three layers -->
  <section class="bg-cream-warm/40 border-y border-ink/10">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 mb-16">
        <div class="md:col-span-4">
          <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The architecture</p>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-8">
          <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[24ch]">
            Three layers of AI in Course Code<span class="brand-period">.</span>
          </h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Layer 1 -->
        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-6">
            <div class="md:col-span-3">
              <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Layer 01</p>
              <p class="font-display text-xl text-ink">AI as co-founder<span class="brand-period">.</span></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-2">Development</p>
            </div>
            <div class="md:col-span-9 max-w-reading">
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
                My AI co-founder runs on OpenClaw plus Anthropic's Claude. Sonnet for execution.
                Opus for strategy. She has her own GitHub account, her own Linear user, API keys
                to every production system, QA authority, and deploy access.
              </p>
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
                Model split was a deliberate product decision. Opus for strategy is
                expensive but worth it. Sonnet for execution is fast and cheap. Subagents
                for isolated tasks mean no context bleed, no token waste. This discipline
                reduced AI operating costs by roughly 80% from early undisciplined usage.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Layer 2 -->
        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-6">
            <div class="md:col-span-3">
              <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Layer 02</p>
              <p class="font-display text-xl text-ink">Claude in the product<span class="brand-period">.</span></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-2">Intelligence</p>
            </div>
            <div class="md:col-span-9 max-w-reading">
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
                The Anthropic SDK is a direct production dependency in package.json. Claude isn't just how Course Code was built. It's running inside Course Code.
              </p>
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
                The data extraction pipeline uses Claude to normalize and structure dress
                code data from course websites. Dress codes live in PDFs, buried website
                pages, and inconsistently formatted club rules documents. Claude handles
                the extraction and normalization at a quality level no regex pipeline
                could match.
              </p>
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
                The moat isn't having 4,659 courses. Anyone can scrape that. The moat is
                verified data plus a women's POV editorial layer plus a brand voice that
                sounds like a friend who plays a lot of golf. Claude is what makes that
                scalable without losing quality.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Layer 3 -->
        <div class="bg-cream p-8 md:p-10 border border-ink/10">
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-6">
            <div class="md:col-span-3">
              <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">Layer 03</p>
              <p class="font-display text-xl text-ink">n8n for operations<span class="brand-period">.</span></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-2">Automation</p>
            </div>
            <div class="md:col-span-9 max-w-reading">
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Self-hosted n8n handles the automation layer that keeps the business
                running without manual intervention. Weekly health reports route from
                PostHog to Slack. Klaviyo nurture sequences fire on onboarding completion.
                Linear webhooks activate my AI co-founder when I move a ticket.
              </p>
              <p class="text-ink-soft leading-relaxed">
                Why n8n instead of cron jobs? Cost. Six daily cron jobs running through
                the main AI session were burning $400 a month at peak. Migrating to n8n
                isolated the workflows, removed the context overhead, and got costs under
                control. Operational automation should be cheap and durable. AI inference
                should be reserved for work that actually requires reasoning.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cost discipline -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-16">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Cost discipline</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight max-w-[18ch]">
          The part most AI evangelists skip<span class="brand-period">.</span>
        </h2>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 max-w-reading">
        <div class="prose-mc">
          <p>
            Running AI at production scale without cost controls is how you burn $13 in one
            morning because a heartbeat cron started reading a bloated JSON file. I learned
            this the expensive way.
          </p>
          <p>
            The rules I built:
          </p>
        </div>

        <ul class="not-prose space-y-4 mt-8">
          {[
            { rule: 'No new cron jobs without explicit approval', why: 'Crons compound. Each one adds a fixed recurring cost forever.' },
            { rule: 'Model split is non-negotiable', why: 'Sonnet for execution. Opus for strategy only. Haiku for fallbacks.' },
            { rule: 'Session hygiene', why: 'New topic, new session. Long sessions compound token burn exponentially. Fresh sessions are cheaper, not worse, when memory is solid.' },
            { rule: 'Subagents for big work', why: 'Coding over 50 lines, deep research, anything that would bloat the main session context.' },
            { rule: 'Root file size limits', why: 'Heartbeat files under 1KB. Core workspace files only at root. Everything else in subdirectories. Root files auto-load on every session.' },
            { rule: 'Archive aggressively', why: 'Done tasks move out of active context. Ship log lives in reference, not in working memory.' },
          ].map((row) => (
            <li class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-4 py-4 border-t border-ink/10">
              <div class="md:col-span-5">
                <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink">{row.rule}<span class="text-orange">.</span></p>
              </div>
              <div class="md:col-span-7 text-ink-soft">{row.why}</div>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>

        <div class="prose-mc mt-10">
          <p>
            The result: AI operating costs went from unpredictable and escalating to
            controlled and predictable. The model split alone cut costs by roughly 80%.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What changed -->
  <section class="bg-ink text-cream py-24 md:py-32">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-cream/60 mb-6">What actually changed</p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-cream leading-tight mb-16 max-w-[24ch]">
        The bottleneck shifted from execution to clarity<span class="text-orange">.</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 md:gap-16">
        <div class="max-w-reading">
          <p class="font-display text-2xl text-orange mb-4">Before<span class="text-cream">.</span></p>
          <p class="text-lg text-cream/80 leading-relaxed">
            Blocked on "how long will this take to build."
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="max-w-reading">
          <p class="font-display text-2xl text-orange mb-4">After<span class="text-cream">.</span></p>
          <p class="text-lg text-cream/80 leading-relaxed">
            Blocked on "exactly what do I want this to do."
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="md:col-span-2 max-w-reading mt-8">
          <p class="text-lg text-cream/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Spec quality became the highest-leverage skill I have. When AI handles
            execution, every decision that stays with me became more consequential. I'm
            not reviewing PRs. I'm making brand calls, pricing decisions, positioning
            choices. The things that actually determine whether this company succeeds.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-cream/80 leading-relaxed">
            This is the counterintuitive truth about delegating execution to AI: it
            doesn't make your job less important. It makes it more important, because
            your judgment is now the actual bottleneck.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The larger point -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24 md:py-32">
    <div class="max-w-reading">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-6">The larger point</p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-display-md text-ink leading-tight mb-10">
        The question every product leader should be asking in 2026<span class="brand-period">.</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="prose-mc">
        <p>
          The question isn't "how do I use AI to work faster." It's "how do I redesign
          the operating model of this business around what AI can actually do?"
        </p>
        <p>
          Those are different questions with very different answers. The first question
          leads to better copy, faster research, and autocomplete that knows your
          codebase. Useful. Incremental.
        </p>
        <p>
          The second question leads to an AI with a GitHub account, a Linear queue, QA
          authority, and a soul document. It leads to a solo founder shipping at team
          velocity. It leads to a new kind of operating leverage that doesn't require
          hiring to access.
        </p>
        <p>
          That's what I built with Course Code. And that's what I bring to every product
          org I work in.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12">
        <a
          href="/work/course-code"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-3 px-6 py-3 bg-orange text-cream font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] hover:bg-orange-deep transition-colors"
        >
          Read the Course Code case study →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
